>On Tue, 19 Feb 2002, incynr8 wrote:
>
> > Does anyone thing lojack and/or alarms help? Are most of these being
> > towed away in the dark of night, or hot wired and driven away?
>
>Pro thieves use tow trucks.  Alarms will only help if you are within
>earshot, as people tend to ignore them due to excessive false alarms.
>Lojack is better, and they claim a 90% recovery rate.  The trick is to get
>to the vehicle before they disable the lojack or put the vehicle into a
>metal building.
>
> > The other thing,I was thinking, for longer term storage and shows was a
> > wheel boot.
>
>It would slow them down, but a pro will just winch it up onto his flatbed
>and drive away.  Better to chain it (with a hefty chain) to something
>substantial, or just to put it up on blocks and store the wheels
>elsewhere.
>
>Practically, in a parking lot, a club on the steering wheel with the
>wheels turned fully right or left will discourage a tow-truck equipped
>thief, as they cannot tow the car out of the space without it hitting
>adjacent cars.
>
>Of course, there is the classic Doberman on a long chain.
>
>George
